  "prompt": "What is the change in Indian economy after demonetisation?",
  "response": "Demonetization in India, implemented on November 8, 2016, by Prime Minister Narendra Modi, had several significant impacts on the Indian economy:\n\nPositive Effects:\n1. Increased digital transactions\n2. Reduced cash circulation\n3. Improved tax compliance\n4. Higher banking penetration\n5. Temporary reduction in black money\n\nNegative Effects:\n1. Short-term economic slowdown\n2. Reduced GDP growth rate\n3. Job losses, especially in informal sectors\n4. Disruption in small and medium enterprises\n5. Cash shortage and economic inconvenience\n\nSpecific Economic Changes:\n1. Formal economic sector expansion\n2. Increased bank deposits\n3. Greater financial transparency\n4. Enhanced digital payment infrastructure\n5. Reduced cash-based transactions\n\nLong-term Impacts:\n1. Gradual formalization of the economy\n2. Improved tax collection\n3. Increased financial inclusion\n4. Technological advancement in banking\n5. Shift towards digital payment systems\n\nChallenges:\n1. Initial economic disruption\n2. High currency replacement costs\n3. Temporary reduction in consumer spending\n4. Impact on cash-dependent sectors\n\nWhile demonetization aimed to curb black money and corruption, its overall economic impact remains complex and debated among economists.",
